"The Mandalorian & Grogu (2026)" marks the Mandalorian saga’s thrilling return to the big screen under the visionary direction of Jon Favreau, with a screenplay co-written by Favreau and Dave Filoni. This highly anticipated film transports fan-favorite duo Din Djarin and Grogu from their Disney+ appearances into a cinematic scale adventure. Pedro Pascal reprises his role as the stoic Din Djarin, while Grogu continues to captivate audiences through a blend of animatronics, puppetry, and advanced visual effects.

Joining Pascal and Grogu is an esteemed ensemble cast: Sigourney Weaver stars as a commanding New Republic colonel named Ward, who oversees critical missions following the fall of the Empire. Jeremy Allen White voices the now-grown Rotta the Hutt—once Jabba’s son—taking him in a new, muscular gladiator direction. Jonny Coyne returns as the imposing Imperial warlord leading remnants of the Empire, while characters like Garazeb “Zeb” Orrelios and members of the Anzellan species make appearances, deepening the narrative continuity with the Disney+ series.

Scheduled for release on May 22, 2026, "The Mandalorian & Grogu" serves as the first theatrical installment in the Star Wars franchise since The Rise of Skywalker (2019). Although a trailer has not yet been released to the public, exclusive footage debuted at D23 2024 and Star Wars Celebration 2025, offering glimpses of Grogu training, AT-ATs in snowy terrain, and exciting action sequences. Directed and produced by Favreau, with Kathleen Kennedy and Dave Filoni also at the helm, the film promises to deliver a standalone cinematic experience that both longtime fans and newcomers can enjoy.
